    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Hey, i'm just starting to learn music theory and i keep hearing about the \"circle of fifths.\" can u explain how it actually works and how i'm supposed to use it to figure out what key a song is in?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The Circle of Fifths is a diagram that maps out all 12 musical keys in a circle, where each key is a perfect fifth away from the next one. It's a magical tool that lets you instantly know the relative major and minor keys, their sharps and flats, and even their \"home\" notes without doing any math.\n\nTo figure out what key a song is in, you simply look at the key signature on the sheet music and find where it sits on the circle. If the song has one sharp (F#), you'll find it on the key labeled \"G Major\" or \"E Minor,\" which are the two keys that share that signature. If the song has two sharps (C# and G#), you'll find it on the \"A Major\" or \"F# Minor\" keys.\n\nYou can also use the circle to find the relative minor key, which shares the same key signature but starts on the third note of the major scale. For example, if you see the key of C Major on the circle, the relative minor is A Minor, sitting right below it on the same line. This makes it incredibly easy to spot the tonal center of a song just by glancing at",
      "source": "target",
